		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Hirsch report</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>See also <a href="/wiki/Robert_L._Hirsch" title="Robert L. Hirsch">Robert L. Hirsch</a><br />
The <b>Hirsch report</b>, the commonly referred to name for the report <b>Peaking of World Oil Production: Impacts, Mitigation, and Risk Management</b>, was created by request for the <a href="/wiki/US_Department_of_Energy" title="US Department of Energy" class="mw-redirect">US Department of Energy</a> and published in February 2005. It examined the likelihood of the occurrence of <a href="/wiki/Peak_oil" title="Peak oil">peak oil</a>, the necessary mitigating actions, and the likely impacts based on the timeliness of those actions.</p>
<p>The Lead Author, <a href="/wiki/Robert_L._Hirsch" title="Robert L. Hirsch">Robert Hirsch</a>, published <a href="http://www.acus.org/docs/051007-Hirsch_World_Oil_Production.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.acus.org/docs/051007-Hirsch_World_Oil_Production.pdf" rel="nofollow">a brief summary of this report</a> in October 2005 for the Atlantic Council.</p>
